LocationComment: Suburban, 4 miles from Springfield, Illinois-a city of more than 100,000. The observation location is the rear of a split level home which obscures much of the light coming from Springfield. One neighbor's porch visible and obstructive. Light halo from Springfield is not visible on this side of the apex.  Light sources visible from location include interior lights from nearby residences, 1 street light--obscured by trees. Structures include a two car garage, and nearby homes, but the observation point is high enough that structures only obscure view of horizon and the lowest stars. There are trees present to the south, but at this point in the year, they do little to obscure the view. A little snow cover, but much has melted and reflected light is minimal. No moon. All in all, after allowing a few minutes for the eye to adjust, one can see satellites with relative ease.

My eyes lose about a magnitude compared with average vision, so I prefer to trust the SQM reading.  I am providing here a mean of several measures taken with a narrow-FOV SQM #2791, i.e. 19.89 mag.   (A wide-band SQM # 1277 takes in more pollution to the West and more Milky Way to the East - and gave readings about a third of a magnitude brighter i.e. ~19.56 mag).  No obvious glow above the Coquimbo stadium (clear air).
LocationComment: Outer suburban garden east of La Serena-Coquimbo conurbation (which now has about 439,230 inhabitants and is growing at a rate of 32% per decade).  No snow (southern summer).  No street lights or other light sources in SQM beam.  White lights are on at the the Coquimbo football stadium about 10km? to the SW.

SkyComment: My eyesight is 20/10 in both eyes and for me, visibility was better than I indicated but is very accurately assessed: most other normally-sited people agree with my assessment as indicated.    There was a very strong wind blowing and those people running asteroid tracking programs indicated tht the bloom was about the worst they've seen in a while.  It was just slightly hazy, with less than one-tenth cloud cover of stratiform clouds.  I believe that dust was a factor to be dealt with.  Estimated wind strength was 25-35 knots with peak gusts up to 50 knots.    (I am a retired  airline pilot of 42 years experience, and was a certified weather observer for NOAA in Fort Yukon, AK  in 1977.)
LocationComment: N37 degrees 49 min 09 sec  W122 degrees 10 min 54 sec    Chabot  Space and Science Center,  Oakland, CA. USA    Observation made atop a forested Hill 1500 feet above the East Bay of Oakland CA

SkyComment: The sky was very clear tonight and I could see a good amount of stars. Tonight was great observing conditions as major stars and constellations were clearly visible. I was able to identify Venus, Jupiter, Mars and all stars within Orion, Leo, and the big and little dippers. There was some haze and some stratus clouds dispersed on the lower level of the sky towards the ground, however, they did not affect the visibility of the stars that are higher in the sky.
LocationComment: I observed the night sky at Nichol Park on New London Road in Landenberg, Pennsylvania. This is a very rural area. The park is a large open field that is surrounded by trees. There are not many structures around it, however, there were a few houses interspersed on the road on the side of the park. It was very dark which really helped to be able to see the stars and planets in the sky. The only light sources in the vicinity of the area where we observed the sky was the headlights from the cars driving by on the road next to the park. There were no street lights or light posts at the park, so besides from the cars driving by, it was very dark.

It's luminosity is about the same as yesterday: I have to squint a bit to be sure it is actually there. I also think that I see stars surrounding the stars farthest away from the reddish star. These stars are more to the south. In between the group of stars and the reddish star are two of the brightest stars tonight. The clouds move northward.

The sky was slightly cloudy with barely any haze. I chose magnitude 1 because I can see the starts clearly. The starts were a bright white which allowed me to enjoy the view even more. Since the sky was clear, I was able to spot Orions belt quickly. When facing south, I spotted Orion on my right (southwest). I am not completely familiar with Orions shape so I choose to spot the belt first and work my way to figure out Orions shape. The lights around the development had no influence on my ability to see the stars. There is definitely a large contrast between the points of the light and the darkness around. I noticed that on campus, I do not really see the brightness of the stars because of the lights coming out of the dorms. However, when seeing the starts outside the parking with few lighting, I was able to notice the brightness of the starts even more.
LocationComment: Suburban area. Right outside the parking lot of a townhouse development. No streetlights, no porch lights, no snow cover. There were only two very dim tan color light-polls at the right end and left end of the street. There were also small trees in the parking lot. The biggest one was behind me so it did not block my view. From where I was standing, I had a good view of the night sky. No streets blocking or lights distracting my view. In conclusion, location was fairly good and appropriate to look at the night sky

SkyComment: Looking for Leo was very difficult.  Although the sky was clear and barely clouded, I am not too familiar with Leo. I had to keep referring to the instruction online to find Leo. I looked for the North Start first, then work my way south to find Leo. Once I figured out Leos tail, it was easier to spot him when I looked away. The lights around the development had no influence on my ability to see the stars. There is definitely a large contrast between the points of the light and the darkness around. I noticed that on campus, I do not really see the brightness of the stars because of the lights coming out of the dorms. However, when seeing the starts outside the parking with few lighting, I was able to notice the brightness of the starts even more. Although the sky was clear, Leo was harder to find the Orion. Leo does not have a distinct figure like Orion. I found Orion easier to find because of the belt which is unique. I definitely appreciate the sky night better after this project.

In conclusion, location was fairly good and appropriate to look at the night sky

SkyComment: I observed the sky from my girlfriend's house in Harford County, Maryland. The latitude is 39.656914 and the longitude is -76.530059 at the exact location at which I observed. The night was perfectly clear. Harford County is out in the country so there is very little light pollution. I can say that I have never seen so many stars in the sky in my life. It was a surreal experience. I am from a town similar to Newark, so I have never really seen the actual night sky without the effects of light pollution. The magnitude at this location must have been around 1 or 2, I cannot imagine the night sky being much more clear. I just thought about how in early civilizations there was no real light pollution like there is today, so the stars must have amazed those people. It used to be odd to think that people got so much use from the stars in the old days because I have not (due to light pollution). But after seeing them, I wish that there was less pollution because seeing n illuminated night sky is a joy that everyone should have, every night.   The night sky itself was unbelievable. I was able to see the night sky filled with stars. The backdrop was so dark that each star light up like a pinpoint of intense light. The color was invasive. Points of light lit up everywhere and created an intricate pattern across the sky. It was easy to identify constellations such as Orion. It was also easy to create shapes in my own mind, similar to how children make shapes out of the clouds. The night sky was an amazing thing to see. Overall, it was a great experience to see a night sky without the effects of light pollution. I hope to see more skies like this, so hopefully something can be done about light pollution to encourage viewing the night sky.

The color of the sky was a dark purple while I was observing, which made the stars stand out more. The constellation Orion was especially bright, and there were a few dimmer surrounding stars. LocationComment: Suburban college town with a lot of lights (for campus safety purposes). At least one large lamppost every fifteen feet, with other sources of light emitting from residence hall windows and the hotel next door. Trees here are very spread out and generally similar in height and width for aesthetic purposes, with a small thicket of leafy ones to separate the campus buildings from the privately owned ones. The buildings are plentiful but low to the ground; most are no more than four or five floors, with the exception being two apartment towers which emit more light from a radio transmitter on the roof. There is a main road nearby so the area has a fair amount of car traffic, and the headlights passing by generate another consistent source of light.

SkyComment: There was little clouds after the sun went down and it was a little bit cloudy at the skyline because of evaporated water from the sea nearby. However, we were lucky enough to observe all the beautiful things of the winter night and by naked eyes, we saw most of Northern stars. We could also obser the planets: Venus, Jupiter, Mars and Saturn. Later, we intended to observe M42 but a thin fog prevented us. Fortunately, we did wait till nearly 2:00 am and all the DSOs' treasures were revealed. Nothing more to expect for urban children like us!
LocationComment: Binh Chau - Phuoc Buu Natural Reservation located in Ba Ria - Vung Tau Province, Vietnam. There was no lights or bulbs except of few lights from our camp. There also was a basin at the heart of the reservation, an interesting place for lying down and observe. It is wide enough to make the trees, which take about 10 degree in the skyline, become shorter. That's it, a perfect stargazing destination.

SkyComment: The sky was clear.  While there was some increased sky glow in the southwest direction (in the direction of the main highway), it was slightly less than in previous years, mainly due to a number of local businesses turning off their outdoor signs after closing as well as the number of vacant stores on the highway.    The area around Leo was actually intermediate between the Magnitude 4 chart and the Magnitude 5 chart.  When factoring in stars that were flickering in and out of visibility, the view was closer to the Magnitude 5 chart.  Using my method of looking for the dimmest star definitely visible in the area and looking it up on Cartes du Ciel (a computer sky chart program) to get the magnitude, I arrived at an estimate of magnitude 4.6, which is about par for this location on a clear moonless night.  Had I observed from the backyard, subject to the direct glare of the floodlights I mentioned in the location comments, the magnitude figure might get to 4 if I was lucky.
LocationComment: The location is suburban.  There is a streetlight across the street in front of the house.  A neighbor to one side has a floodlight.  Another individual in the neighborhood has a bright floodlight mounted on the second floor of his oversized house.  There are two enormous trees in the back and side yards plus one monstrous tree in the front yard.  Sighting had to wait until Leo was in an area of sky unobstructed by trees.  Observed from the side of the detached garage which blocked the direct light of the floodlights and the house blocked the direct light of the streetlight.
